Name: House of Commons
Notes:
The House of Commons is the lower house of the UK Parliament.  The House of Commons and House of Lords make the law of the United Kingdom through Acts of Parliament.  Each Act requires Royal Assent before it becomes law.

The House of Commons also holds the Government to account.

Name: House of Lords
Notes: The House of Lords is the upper house of the UK Parliament. The House of Commons and House of Lords make the law of the United Kingdom through Acts of Parliament. Each Act requires Royal Assent before it becomes law.

Name: Department for Business, Enterprise and Regulatory Reform
Notes: On the 5th of June 2009 the Government created a new Department for Business, Innovation and Skills. The Department was created by merging BERR and DIUS. FOI requests to the successor department can be made via: http://www.whatdotheyknow.com/body/bis

Name: Home Office
Notes: The Home Office is the lead government department for immigration and crime. The Home Office's areas of responsibility include police, counter-terrorism, passports and drugs policy. The Home Office is lead by the Home Secretary and five other ministers.[2] The Home Office is often referred to in official documents and in Parliament by its former name 'the Home Department'.[3]

Name: British Educational Communications and Technology Agency
Her Majesty's Courts and the Tribunals Service
Notes: Freedom of Information Requests to courts including magistrates courts, county courts, the high court and appeal courts can be made via the Courts and Tribunals Service. From 1 April 2011, Her Majesty's Courts Service and the Tribunals Service integrated to form Her Majesty's Courts and Tribunals Service.[1] Freedom of Information Requests to HMCTS are dealt with by the Ministry of Justice's FOI team. Please make clear within your request that you are seeking information held by HMCTS. WhatDoTheyKnow lists the UK Supreme Court, The High Court of Justiciary [Scotland] and The Judicial Committee of the Privy Council separately.

Name: Ministry of Justice
Notes: The Ministry of Justice is one of the largest government departments, employing over 70,000 people.

Name: Department for Culture, Media and Sport
Department of Health
Notes: The Department of Health (DH) exists to improve the health and wellbeing of people in England.[1] The Department provides strategic leadership to the NHS and social care organisations in England.[2] FOI requests relating to Connecting for Health, the national programme for NHS information technology, including summary care records, can be made to the Department of Health. Connecting for Health is a directorate of the Department of Health. Requests to the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) can also be made via the Department for Health.

Name: Department for Children, Schools and Families
Notes: On the 12 May 2010 the Government created a new Department for Education. FOI requests to the successor department can be made via: http://www.whatdotheyknow.com/body/dfe

Name: Department for Innovation, Universities and Skills
Notes: On the 5th of June 2009 the Government created a new Department for Business, Innovation and Skills. The Department was created by merging BERR and DIUS. FOI requests to the successor department can be made via: http://www.whatdotheyknow.com/body/bis

Name: Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs
Her Majesty's Treasury
Notes: Her Majesty's Treasury is the UK government department responsible for public finance policy and economic policy.[1] The Treasury maintains the Combined Online Information System (COINS) containing a detailed analysis of government spending under thousands of category headings.[2] The Chancellor of the Exchequer has overall responsibility for the work of Treasury.[3]

Name: Privy Council Office
Notes:
See also:

Name: Department for Work and Pensions
Notes: The DWP is responsible for welfare and pension policy, it is the largest of all UK Government Departments.[1] Requests to the Pensions Service, Disabilities and Carers Service and Jobcentre plus can be made via the DWP which is their parent department. The Department is lead by the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions.

Name: Department for International Development
Notes: The Department for International Development (DFID) is the part of the UK government that manages the UK's aid to poorer countries and aims to eliminate extreme poverty. DFID has offices in around 40 developing countries. The department is lead by the secretary of state for international development. The International Development Act (Reporting and Transparency) 2006 requires the secretary of state to report every year on how much money was spent on aid, how effective the spending has been.

Name: Department for Communities and Local Government
Notes: DCLG is responsible for National Planning Casework Unit.

Name: Cabinet Office
Notes: The Cabinet Office is a department of the Government of the United Kingdom responsible for supporting the Prime Minister and Cabinet.[1] The Cabinet Office is responsible ensuring effective development, coordination and implementation of policy and operations across all government departments.[1] See also Prime Minister's Office.

Name: British Broadcasting Corporation
Notes:
The British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) is a public broadcaster in the UK and one of the largest broadcasting organisation in the world.[1] The BBC is funded by the TV licence fee that is paid by UK households and business who have televisions.[1] The BBC is independent from direct government intervention, its activities being overseen by the BBC Trust.[2] The BBC provides eight national TV channels (BBC One, BBC Two, BBC Three, BBC Four, CBBC, CBeebies, BBC News, BBC Parliament) as well as radio broadcasting, BBC Online and BBC iPlayer.[3]

'TV Licensing' is a trade mark of the BBC and is used under licence by companies paid to administer the collection of TV licence fees and enforcement of TV licensing on behalf of the BBC.[4]

Under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 you have the right to ask for information from the BBC except for information the BBC holds for the purposes of journalism, art or literature.

Name: Environment Agency
Notes: The Environment Agency is an Executive Non-departmental Public Body.  Its principal aims are to protect and improve the environment, and to promote sustainable development.

Name: General Register Office
Notes: Also known as the "National Register Office"

Name: Central Office of Information
Notes: The Central Office of Information closed on 31st March 2012.

Name: Ministry of Defence
Notes: The Ministry of Defence (MOD) is the UK government department responsible for implementation of government defence policy and for the British Armed Forces.[1] The MoD manages the day to day running of the armed forces, contingency planning and defence procurement. The military professional structure is embodied in the three single Services (the Royal Navy, Army, and the Royal Air Force).[1]

Name: Department for Transport
Notes: The Department for Transport (Welsh: Adran am Drafnidiaeth) is the government department responsible for the English transport network and a limited number of transport matters in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland which are not devolved.  DfT is run by the Secretary of State for Transport. The work of DfT used to be carried out by the Ministry of Transport, this name lives on in 'MOT' test.

Name: Cheshire County Council
Notes:
On 1st April 2009, Chester City and Cheshire County Councils split their combined area and become two unitary authorities - Cheshire West and Chester, and Cheshire East. The existing councils of Ellesmere Port and Neston, Chester, Crewe and Nantwich, Congleton, Macclesfield and Vale Royal are abolished.

Cheshire East Council is formed from Macclesfield Borough Council, Congleton and Crewe & Nantwich Borough Councils, together with part of Cheshire County Council.

Cheshire West & Chester Council is formed from Ellesmere Port & Neston, Chester & Vale Royal councils, together with part of Cheshire County Council.

Cheshire East Council will take responsibility for any in-progress FOI reviews. Those requests originally submitted to Cheshire County Council and which are subject to review will be dealt with jointly by Cheshire East and Cheshire West.

Cheshire East Council is now the custodian of information previously held by the District and County councils; any requests for this information should be directed to the new council.

All new FOI requests for information held by the former Cheshire County Council should be made to Cheshire East Council

Notes: HMRC was formed on the in April 2005, following the merger of Inland Revenue and Her Majesty's Customs and Excise Departments. HMRC is responsible for the administration and collection of taxes and duties including income tax, corporation tax, National Insurance and VAT. HMRC pays and administers Child Benefit, Child Trust Fund and Tax Credits. In addition, HMRC are responsible for National Minimum Wage enforcement and the recovery of student loans.[1] HMRC also maintains the Business Link website the government's online resource for businesses.

Name: UK Border Agency
Notes:
As of the 1st of April 2013 what was the UK Border Agency has now become two units within the Home Office.

Freedom of Information Requests should therefore be directed to the successor body: The Home Office.

For more information see the Home Secretary' statement to the commons on the 26 of March 2013 on the abolition of the UK Border Agency

The former UK Border Agency website states: "On 1 April 2013 the UK Border Agency was split into two separate units within the Home Office: a visa and immigration service and an immigration law enforcement division"

Enquiries relating to individual immigration and nationality cases must not be made via WhatDoTheyKnow. To get in touch with the UKBA directly please click here for direct contact information for the UKBA.

The UK Border Agency formed in April 2008 as a merger of the Border and Immigration Agency (BIA), UKVisas and the port of entry functions of HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC).

The UKBA replaced what used to be called the Immigration and Nationality Directorate (IND).

The full text, including the email addresses, provided by the UKBA in their standard FAQ reply to some requests is available at: here.

Name: Common Council of the City of London
Notes: Under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 you can request information from the Common Council of the City of London about the work it carries out as a local authority, police authority or port health authority. The Common Council is the local authority for the "Square Mile" only (the historic City of London) and not for London as a whole. The City of London Police Authority is listed separately. We also list Guildhall School of Music and Drama separately. We also list City of London Corporation separately, for those who wish request information from other parts of the Corporation.

Name: Durham City Council
Notes:
On 1st April 2009 Durham County Council became a unitary authority. The councils of the City of Durham, Easington, Sedgefield, Teesdale, Wear Valley, Derwentside, and Chester-le-Street were abolished.

All new FOI requests for information held by the former Durham City Council should be made to Durham County Council http://www.whatdotheyknow.com/body/durham_county_council

Name: Ellesmere Port and Neston Borough Council
Notes:
On 1st April 2009, Chester City and Cheshire County Councils split their combined area and become two unitary authorities - Cheshire West and Chester, and Cheshire East. The existing councils of Ellesmere Port and Neston, Chester, Crewe and Nantwich, Congleton, Macclesfield and Vale Royal are abolished.

Cheshire East Council is formed from Macclesfield Borough Council, Congleton and Crewe & Nantwich Borough Councils, together with part of Cheshire County Council.

Cheshire West & Chester Council is formed from Ellesmere Port & Neston, Chester & Vale Royal councils, together with part of Cheshire County Council.

Cheshire East Council will take responsibility for any in-progress FOI reviews. Those requests originally submitted to Cheshire County Council and which are subject to review will be dealt with jointly by Cheshire East and Cheshire West.

Cheshire East Council is now the custodian of information previously held by the District and County councils; any requests for this information should be directed to the new council.

All new FOI requests for information held by the former Ellesmere Port & Neston Borough Council should be made to Cheshire West & Chester Council
http://www.whatdotheyknow.com/body/cheshire_east_council
http://www.whatdotheyknow.com/body/cheshire_west_chester_council

The National Grid is subject to the Environmental Information Regulations (EIR) due to their designation as a "holder of a transmission licence" [Energy Act 2004 (Designation of System Operator) Order 2004].

However, be warned that National Grid have written to the WhatDoTheyKnow.com team to say: "The information requests submitted to date, (or in the future, for that matter) will not receive a response from National Grid plc via the 'WhatDoTheyKnow.com' website. However, National Grid plc would be happy to consider any reasonable request for environmental information made direct to National Grid plc".

Despite this, we encourage you to make your request to National Grid plc in public using WhatDoTheyKnow. If they do not answer it, we recommend that you complain to the Information Commissioner.

Name: Centre for the Protection of National Infrastructure
Notes:
According to http://www.cpni.gov.uk/foi.aspx , CPNI is accountable to the Director General of the Security Service (MI5) and therefore operates under the Security Service Acts 1989 and 1996. CPNI is not subject to FOIA and therefore will not process FOIA requests.

Under Regulation 4 of the Environmental Information Regulations (EIR), environmental information relevant to the functions of the Security Service, which does not adversely affect national security can be requested.

Name: Government Communications Headquarters
Notes:

CSEG runs GovCertUK, the Computer Emergency Response Team (CERT) for the UK Government.[1]

Name: Independent Monitoring Boards Secretariat
Notes:
Independent Monitoring Boards (IMB) work inside every prison and immigration removal centre. They are a group of ordinary members of the public, and they monitor the day-to-day life in their local prison or removal centre and ensure that proper standards of care and decency are maintained.

Use the Secretariat for FOI requests relating to IMBs generally. If your query relates to a specific IMB, please make the request to them directly.

Name: Glasgow Housing Association Limited
Tags: foi_voluntary scotland limited public_function housing_association company
Notes:
This Housing Association is not subject to the Freedom of Information (Scotland) Act 2002.

They have indicated that they do respond to reasonable requests for information, in the spirit of the Act: "GHA's openness and confidentiality policy states that; "Although not bound by the Freedom of Information Act (which currently does not extend to RSLs), GHA is not bound by, but aims to meet the spirit of the legislation."

Please note that you will not be able to complain to the Scottish Information Commissioner if you are dissatisfied with their response.

Housing Associations may be subject to the Environmental Information Regulations.

The Scottish Government has proposed to formally extend the FOI laws to GHA, this is still under discussion.

Name: The Corporation of Trinity House of Deptford Strond
Notes: Trinity House is not subject to the Freedom of Information Act 2000, however, Trinity House has agreed to act within the spirit of the Act, and as such will provide information when requested, with the exception of information that is exempt under the Freedom of Information Act 2000. Trinity House is the General Lighthouse Authority for England, Wales, the Channel Islands and Gibraltar. The Corporation is also a Deep Sea Pilotage Authority. The statutory responsibilities of Trinity House are set out in the Merchant Shipping Act 1995. On 7 January 2011 the Government announced a consultation on extending the scope of the Freedom of Information to cover additional bodies. This authority is referred to in the announcement.

We have been advised that Ministry of Justice rather then the Supreme Court is responsible for dealing with any FOI queries concerning the Constitutional Reform Act 2005 including the creation of the Supreme Court, the Supreme Court Implementation Programme and the refurbishment of the Middlesex Guildhall.

Name: Church of Scotland
Notes:
The Church of Scotland is not subject to the Freedom of Information (Scotland) Act 2002. It does however answer requests for information as a matter of policy: "Church bodies should adopt the presumption that all information should be made available or disclosed on request unless special considerations dictate otherwise." Source: Guidance Notes on Freedom of Information within the Church, a law department circular.[1][2] While the Church of Scotland is not an established church its constitution, it is the official church of Scotland.[3] The Church has special legal protection by the Church of Scotland Act 1921.

The email address used here is for 'Finance and Stewardship'.

Name: British Film Institute

The BFI is included in the Whole of Government Accounts and was established by a Royal Charter. The BFI receives its grant-in-aid from the Department for Culture Media and Sport via the UK Film Council. FOI requests to the UK Film Council can be made via this link. BFI is a registered charity regulated by the Charity Commission.

Name: Stabilisation Unit
Notes: The Stabilisation Unit is the Government's centre of expertise in stabilisation. The unit is home to the Civilian Stabilisation Group (CSG). The Unit works with countries to assist them in building capacity for self-government. The Unit reports to the Ministry of Defence, Foreign and Commonwealth Office and Department for International Development, and includes staff from all three Departments.[1]

Name: The Ombudsman Service Limited
Tags: hasdescription public_regulatory foi_no ombudsman company limited
Notes:
Ombudsman Services is not subject to the Freedom of Information Act 2000.

Ombudsman Services provides independent dispute resolution for the communications, energy, property and copyright licensing sectors.[1]

  • Ombudsman Services: Energy is approved by Ofgem under the Consumers Estate Agents and Redress Act 2008.
  • Ombudsman Services: Communications are approved by Ofcom as an alternative dispute resolution service.
  • Ombudsman Services: Property has been appointed by the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors (RICS) as the ombudsman for chartered surveyors and has also been approved by the Office of Fair Trading (OFT) as an estate agents redress scheme.
  • Ombudsman Services: Copyright Licensing resolves complaints from consumers relating to licences for the public performance of copyright music.

Name: The Authority for Television On Demand
Notes:
ATVOD is the independent co-regulator for the editorial content of UK video on demand services.[1]

Advertising on video on demand services is regulated by the Advertising Standards Authority.[2]

OFCOM designated ATVOD to be the regulator for on demand programme services under S.368A of the Communications Act 2003, a provision added by The Audiovisual Media Services Regulations 2009.

The authority have a published openness and transparency statement saying: "We will endeavour to respond fairly to requests for information, having regard to the public interest in making such information available. "

ATVOD is not formally subject to FOI law, we list it on WhatDoTheyKnow due to its public regulatory role.

Name: Rail Accident Investigation Branch
Notes: The RAIB is an organisation with responsibility for independently investigating railway accidents with the aim of improving safety. RAIB's work covers all UK railways all and tramways in England and Wales. It is part of the Department for Transport, but functionally and operationally independent. The Chief Inspector reports directly to the Secretary of State on accident investigations.[1] The responsibilities of the RAIB are set out in the Railways and Transport Safety Act 2003 (the Act) and the Railways (Accident Investigation and Reporting) Regulations 2005.

Name: Chief Fire Officers Association
Notes:
Please note that the Chief Fire Officers Association is not subject to the FOI Act, so it may not reply to requests.

They make the following statement about FOI requests:

"CFOA is a private company and the Freedom of Information Act does not apply to the Association, since Schedule 1 of the Act does not include a definition which covers CFOA. Nonetheless, CFOA is very willing to place some information in the public domain. This information is published on [the CFOA] web site, mainly as Position Statements.

What CFOA is unable to do is to respond to requests for information under the Act. The organisation is too small and there are too few members of staff to be able to conduct the necessary research and to compile the responses. Accordingly, CFOA is adopting a policy of responding to requests for information only if it is readily available and can be swiftly transmitted to the inquirer. Other requests for information will be politely refused.

Members of the public who are considering making a request for information from a fire and rescue service should contact that service."

Name: Coleford Parish Council, Somerset
Notes:
Coleford is a village and civil parish in Somerset, England, situated on the Mells River in the Mendip Hills five miles west of Frome.

The parish council has responsibility for local issues, including setting an annual precept (local rate) to cover the council's operating costs and producing annual accounts for public scrutiny. The parish council evaluates local planning applications and works with the local police, district council officers, and neighbourhood watch groups on matters of crime, security, and traffic. The parish council's role also includes initiating projects for the maintenance and repair of parish facilities, as well as consulting with the district council on the maintenance, repair, and improvement of highways, drainage, footpaths, public transport, and street cleaning. Conservation matters (including trees and listed buildings) and environmental issues are also the responsibility of the council.

Name: College of Policing
Notes:
The College of Policing was "launched" in December 2012. It is yet to be established in statute; the Government has indicated this will occur as soon as legislative time allows, which is expected to be in 2014. See the college's "about us" page for more information.

The college is a limited company (No. 08235199) and the sole shareholder is the Home Secretary. [Ref. p35 Home Affairs Select Ctte Report]

Name: Church Commissioners
Notes:
The Church Commissioners are not subject to the Freedom of Information Act 2000.

The Church Commissioners are a statutory body established by the Church Commissioners Measure 1947 to manage historic property assets of the Church of England.

In June 2013, it was decided that the Church Commissioners should be included on this site. A number of factors were considered in arriving at this decision including the fact that the Church Commissioners are accountable to Parliament,[1] the fact that various public officials including the Prime Minister serve on the body as part of their role[2] and the body's objectives.

One of the five objectives of the Church Commissioners is: "to be transparent and accountable in organisational activity and internal governance".[3]

Name: Curo Housing Group
Notes:
From Curo's website: "Curo is a group of companies that operate in the social and commercial housing market as well as the care and support sector. Until 2012 we were a group of housing associations trading under a number of names under the Somer Housing Group umbrella. The core of the housing association business was constructed from the former Somer Community Housing Trust (SCHT), which was set up in 1999 following the transfer of housing stock from Bath & North East Somerset Council. SCHT was joined in 2002 by Shape Housing Association (formerly Bath Self Help), a specialist provider of supported housing with around 150 bed spaces. Redland Housing Association, which was founded in 1973, became the newest member of the Group in 2005, bringing with it a further 1,400 homes."

Name: Privy Council
Notes:
The Privy Council is not subject to the Freedom of Information Act 2000.

The Privy Council Office (PCO) is a government department that supports the work of the Privy Council. The PCO is subject to the Freedom of Information Act 2000.

We have taken the decision to list the Privy Council separately on the site partly because the PCO has refused to provide information in its possession that is held on behalf of the Privy Council. The site now allows users to address requests directly to the Privy Council but we acknowledge that a number of practical difficulties remain for those who wish to obtain information held by the Privy Council.

See also: Judicial Committee of the Privy Council (a court of appeal)
